This order shall be served on the local authority by the court.

Domestic abuse issues

[Name] has raised issues of domestic abuse which may be relevant to the court’s determination. The following directions therefore apply:

The issue of domestic abuse will be considered at the FHDRA;

In the meantime the parties are not expected to engage in mediation or other forms of dispute resolution;

(where a party or cafcass has requested special measures or safety arrangements) The court will make enquiries of the [applicant] / [respondent] to find out how they wish to participate in the hearing and to make arrangements to ensure their safety when attending the hearing.

Participation directions

If they have not already done so, any party who considers that specific measures need to be taken to enable a party or witness to understand the proceedings and their role in them when in court, put their views to the court, instruct their representatives before, during, and after the hearing or attend the hearing without significant distress should file an application notice and include the following information as far as practicable:

why the party or witness would benefit from assistance;

the measure or measures that would be likely to maximise as far as practicable the quality of their evidence or participation and why;

written confirmation from any relevant witness of his/her views.

Interpreters

The court shall arrange an interpreter for [name] for all future hearings in the following languages (and dialect if necessary):

[insert].

Applications for permission for experts

Any party intending at the FHDRA to apply for permission to instruct an expert must first comply fully with the requirements of Practice Direction 25C of the Family Procedure Rules including:

The nature of the proceedings and the issues likely to require determination by the court;

The issues in the proceedings which the expert evidence relate to;

The questions which the expert is asked to give an opinion on;

Whether or not permission is sought for the expert to examine the child

Whether or not it will be necessary for the expert to conduct interview and if so, with whom;

The likely timetable and filing date for the report;

Consideration of the whether oral evidence will be required from the expert;

Full details of the experts anticipated costs for the instruction including overall costs, hourly rate, hours to be undertaken, confirmation of legal aid rates, travel, court attendance costs.

